{{Infobox venue | name = Raymond C. Hand Park | nickname = | image = | fullname = | former_names = Governors Park (1970-1993) | location = Drane Street and Farris Drive, [[Clarksville, TN]], United States | coordinates = {{coord|36.537442|-87.355988|display=title,inline}} | broke_ground = | built = 1970 | opened = | renovated = 1993, 2001, 2008 | expanded = 1993 | closed = | demolished = | owner = [[Austin Peay State University]] | operator = Austin Peay State University | surface = | scoreboard = Electronic | estimated_cost = | suites = | architect = | project_manager = | structural engineer = | services engineer = | general_contractor = | main_contractors = | capacity = 1,000 (777 seated) | record_attendance = | executive_suites = | dimensions = 319 ft. ([[Left field|LF]]), 373 ft. (LCF), 392 ft. ([[Baseball field#outfield|CF]]), 365 ft. (RCF), 327 ft. ([[Right field|RF]]) | acreage = | tenants = [[Austin Peay Governors baseball]] ([[Ohio Valley Conference|OVC]]) (1970-present), [[Clarksville Coyotes]] ([[Big South League|BSL]], [[Heartland League|HL]]) (1996-7) }}
'''Raymond C. Hand Park''' is a [[baseball]] venue in [[Clarksville, Tennessee]], United States. It is home to the [[Austin Peay Governors baseball]] team of the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]] [[Ohio Valley Conference]].<ref name=facil>{{cite web|title=Raymond C. Hand Park|url=http://www.apsugovernors.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=16900&ATCLID=3641172|work=APSU Governors|publisher=Austin Peay State Athletic Department|accessdate=20 December 2011|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/645DMmt39|archivedate=2011-12-20}}</ref> The facility has a seated capacity of 777 spectators,<ref name=mg>{{cite web|title=2011 Baseball Media Guide|url=http://issuu.com/letsgopeay/docs/11-bsb-guide|work=Issuu|accessdate=20 December 2011|pages=58|date=March 21, 2011|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/645DQF13h|archivedate=2011-12-20}}</ref> with a total capacity of over 1,000.<ref name="facil" /> The facility opened on March 23, 1970,<ref name="mg" /> and is named for Clarksville businessman Raymond C. Hand.<ref name="facil" />
== History == The park opened on March 23, 1970, as '''Governors Park'''.<ref name="facil" /><ref name="mg" /> In 1993, following renovations led by Clarksville businessman Charles Hand, the park was renamed Raymond C. Hand Park after Hand's father. The park has been the home of Austin Peay State's baseball program since its 1970 construction.<ref name="facil" /> As of the end of the 2010 season, the Governors have a 576-422-2 all-time record at Hand Park.<ref name="mg" />
In 1996 and 1997, the independent professional [[Clarksville Coyotes]] of the [[Big South League]] (1996) and [[Heartland League]] (1997) played at the venue.<ref name=br>{{cite web|last=Merzbach|first=Brian|title=Raymond C. Hand Park: Clarksville, Tennessee|url=http://www.ballparkreviews.com/clarksville/clarksville.htm|work=Ballpark Reviews|accessdate=20 December 2011|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/645DT8UHD|archivedate=2011-12-20}}</ref><ref name=cb>{{cite web|last=O'Reilly|first=Charles|title=Let's Go Peay!|url=http://www.charliesballparks.com/st/TN-Clarksville-Hand.htm|work=Charlie's Ballparks|accessdate=20 December 2011|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/645DUiQoI|archivedate=2011-12-20}}</ref>
== Features and renovations == In 1993, a pair of [[USD|$]]25,000 donations from the estate of Raymond C. Hand led to the installation of stadium lighting and construction of a new seating structure. During 1996 and 1997, when the Clarksville Coyotes shared Hand Park, the team collaborated with the university to add ticket booths, concession stands, and restrooms. In 2001, brick facing was added to the backstop and stadium entrance. In 2008, an eight-foot steel outfield fence was built, including a 12-foot [[batter's eye]].<ref name="facil" /><ref name="mg" />
The field also features an irrigated natural grass surface.<ref name="mg" />
